<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Active Time Listening Mode
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        The Event Point becomes active when the trigger condition is met and remains active for a limited duration controlled by the After Timer field.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Active Time Listening Mode Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Active Time</Bold> creates timed, temporary states that automatically expire after a specific
        duration. When the trigger condition is met, the Event Point becomes active and starts a countdown
        timer. When the After Timer duration expires, the Event Point becomes inactive. This is ideal for
        temporary effects, timed buffs, or objectives with time limits.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Unlike <Bold>Active While</Bold> which depends on a continuous condition, <Bold>Active Time</Bold>
        uses a fixed duration timer. The Event Point stays active for exactly the specified time regardless
        of whether the trigger condition changes.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Use Active Time when the Event Point should be active for a specific duration and then automatically expire. The After Timer field controls how long the Event Point stays active.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        When To Use Active Time
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Active Time</Bold> when the Event Point should be active for a specific duration and then
        automatically expire. This is appropriate for:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,8">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Timed objectives</Bold> - Defend a location for 60 seconds, survive for 2 minutes</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Temporary power-ups</Bold> - Speed boost lasts 10 seconds, invulnerability for 5 seconds</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Time-limited spawns</Bold> - Enemy wave active for 30 seconds then despawns</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Temporary messages</Bold> - Show a hint or warning for 5 seconds then hide it</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Timed dependency windows</Bold> - Other Event Points can depend on this one only during the timer duration</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Fields
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">After Timer</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The duration in game time units that the Event Point remains active after the trigger fires. When
        this timer expires, the Event Point becomes inactive. This field is required when using <Bold>Active Time</Bold>
        listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Example values:</Bold>
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="40,2,0,8">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>100 = approximately 5 seconds</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>200 = approximately 10 seconds</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>1200 = approximately 60 seconds (1 minute)</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Behavior
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When the trigger condition becomes true, the Event Point fires and becomes active. The After Timer
        countdown begins immediately. When the timer expires, the Event Point becomes inactive. If the Event
        Point is triggered again (the trigger condition becomes true again after expiration), the timer
        restarts.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Example:</Bold> A Message Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger, <Bold>Active Time</Bold>
        listening mode, and After Timer = 200 (10 seconds):
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="40,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player enters the radius</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Event Point fires, message appears, Event Point becomes active</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>After Timer countdown begins (200 game time units = ~10 seconds)</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player can leave or stay in the radius — it doesn't matter</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>After 10 seconds, the timer expires</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Event Point becomes inactive, message disappears</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Timed Defense Objective
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A Message Event Point with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active Time</Bold> listening
        mode with After Timer = 1200 (60 seconds). When a previous objective completes, this message appears
        showing "Defend the area for 60 seconds!" and stays visible for exactly 60 seconds. Other Event Points
        can depend on this to track the defense timer.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Temporary Hint Message
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A Message Event Point with <Bold>None</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active Time</Bold> listening mode
        with After Timer = 100 (5 seconds). At mission start, a tutorial hint appears for 5 seconds then
        automatically disappears.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Limited Spawn Window
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A Group Life Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active Time</Bold> listening mode
        with After Timer = 600 (30 seconds). When the player enters an area, enemy reinforcements spawn and
        stay active for 30 seconds. After the timer expires, the Event Point becomes inactive (and the enemies
        may despawn depending on the Event Point configuration).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Timed Dependency Chain
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Event Point A uses <Bold>Active Time</Bold> with After Timer = 400 (20 seconds). Event Point B has
        a <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger on Event Point A. B will only be active during the 20-second window
        when A is active. After A's timer expires, B becomes inactive.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Active Time</Bold> is relatively rare in retail missions but appears in timed objectives and
        temporary tutorial messages. It's commonly used for "hold this position for X seconds" objectives
        where the timer needs to be tracked by the mission system.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Comparison With Other Listening Modes
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Active Time vs Active</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        <Bold>Active Time</Bold> stays active for a limited duration controlled by After Timer. <Bold>Active</Bold>
        stays active permanently once triggered. Use <Bold>Active Time</Bold> for temporary effects that should
        automatically expire. Use <Bold>Active</Bold> for permanent progress markers.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Active Time vs Active While</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        <Bold>Active Time</Bold> uses a fixed duration timer. <Bold>Active While</Bold> is active only while
        the trigger condition remains true. Use <Bold>Active Time</Bold> when you need a specific duration
        regardless of conditions. Use <Bold>Active While</Bold> when the duration depends on a continuous state.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Active Time vs Active Die</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        <Bold>Active Time</Bold> is active for a duration then becomes inactive (but can fire again). <Bold>Active Die</Bold>
        fires once and becomes permanently dead. Use <Bold>Active Time</Bold> for repeatable timed effects.
        Use <Bold>Active Die</Bold> for one-shot cleanup actions.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Active Time Listening Mode Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Identify the Event Point that should be active for a specific duration</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose the appropriate trigger type (None, Dependency, Radius, etc.)</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set Listening Mode to <Bold>Active Time</Bold></Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set After Timer to the desired duration in game time units (e.g., 200 for ~10 seconds)</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Configure trigger-specific fields</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test that the Event Point becomes active when the trigger fires</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Verify the Event Point stays active for the correct duration</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Event Point becomes inactive when the timer expires</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If using as a dependency source, test that dependent Event Points also deactivate when the timer expires</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> After Timer is required for Active Time listening mode. Test your timer values in-game to ensure the duration feels correct. Game time units are approximately 20 units per second.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
